Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Picardie, Frankrijk","Berkeley, Gloucestershire, England":"Berkeley, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"about 0987–":"about 0987–Deceased","0987–Male":"0987–Deceased","0988–Female":"0988–Deceased","1012–1042":"1012–1042","0943–Male":"0943–Deceased","0955–Female":"0955–Deceased","about 0987":"about 0987","975":"0975","1012":"1012","1042":"1042","about 1012":"about 1012","0943":"0943","0987":"0987","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Scotland":"Scotland","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Picardie, France","Berkeley, Gloucestershire, England":"Berkeley, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Berkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Barclay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."]},{"name":"Berkley","meanings":["English: variant of   Berkeley  . Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): assimilated form of   Berkowitz  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Viscount, Roger de Berkeley I Vicount of Berkeley was born about 0987, in Normandy, France, his father, Beoncenlan de Normandie, was 46 and his mother, Eva, was 34. He had at least 1 son with Margaret. He died in Scotland."},"et":{"about 0987–":"umbes 0987–Surnud","0987–Male":"0987–Surnud","0988–Female":"0988–Surnud","1012–1042":"1012–1042","0943–Male":"0943–Surnud","0955–Female":"0955–Surnud","about 0987":"umbes 0987","975":"0975","1012":"1012","1042":"1042","about 1012":"umbes 1012","0943":"0943","0987":"0987","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Scotland":"Scotland","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Berkeley, Gloucestershire, England":"Berkeley, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 0987–":"noin 0987–Kuollut","0987–Male":"0987–Kuollut","0988–Female":"0988–Kuollut","1012–1042":"1012–1042","0943–Male":"0943–Kuollut","0955–Female":"0955–Kuo